content.problem:
Consider the logistic equation:
\[
\frac{dy}{dt} = ry\left(1 - \frac{y}{K}\right)
\]
with $r, K > 0$.

Setting $f(y) = 0$:
\[
ry\left(1 - \frac{y}{K}\right) = 0 \implies y = 0 \text{ or } y = K
\]

The phase line:

center
tikzpicture[scale=0.8]
 % Phase line
 (0,0) – (0,6);

 % Equilibrium points
 lldraw (0,1) circle (3pt) node[right=5pt] {$y = 0$ (unstable)};
 lldraw (0,4) circle (3pt) node[right=5pt] {$y = K$ (stable)};

 % Arrows
 (0,0.3) – (0,0.7);
 (0,1.3) – (0,1.7);
 (0,2) – (0,2.7);
 (0,3) – (0,3.7);
 (0,4.3) – (0,4.7);
 (0,5) – (0,5.5);

 % Labels
 at (0,0) {$-$};
 at (0,2.5) {$+$};
 at (0,5) {$-$};
 at (0,6) {$y$};
tikzpicture
center

Reading the phase line:

- If $y < 0$: $y' < 0$, solution decreases (unphysical for populations)

- If $0 < y < K$: $y' > 0$, solution increases toward $K$

- If $y > K$: $y' < 0$, solution decreases toward $K$

All positive solutions approach $K$ as $t \to \infty$.
